  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>Hannah Arendt sat in a Jerusalem courtroom in 1961 and saw something that frightened her more than a monster. She saw a bureaucrat. Adolf Eichmann — the man who had organized the deportation of millions to their deaths — was not ranting, not seething with hatred, not radiating the demonic charisma the prosecution wanted the world to see. He was fussing over paperwork. He was citing Kant, badly. He was insisting, with the tedious persistence of a middle manager disputing a performance review, that he had simply done his job. Arendt called what she saw "the banality of evil," and the phrase detonated across the intellectual landscape of the twentieth century. Its implications were staggering: if Eichmann was ordinary, then the machinery of genocide did not require extraordinary malice. It required only compliance. The right situation, the right authority, the right pressure — and any of us might do the same.</p>
  <p>That thesis became, for sixty years, the dominant story psychology told about human evil. Stanley Milgram built a laboratory around it. Philip Zimbardo built a fake prison around it. Introductory textbooks wrapped it in a bow and handed it to undergraduates as settled science: <em>situations overwhelm individuals; good people do terrible things because the context demands it; you are not as different from Eichmann as you'd like to believe.</em> The story was meant to be disturbing. But it contained a hidden comfort. If situations make us evil, then nobody is really responsible. We are all equally vulnerable and equally blameless — victims of circumstance, not architects of our own moral failure.</p>
  <p>Modern psychology has closed that escape hatch. And what it found behind the door is worse.</p>
</section>

<section id="milgram-never-showed-blind-obedience" class="reveal">
  <h2>Milgram Never Showed What We Teach</h2>
  <p>The version of Milgram's experiment that lives in the popular imagination is clean and horrifying: 65% of ordinary people, told by a man in a lab coat to administer electric shocks to a screaming stranger, cranked the dial all the way to 450 volts. The lesson, as Milgram told it and as textbooks have repeated it for decades, was that human beings possess a deep-seated tendency to obey authority — so deep that it can override conscience itself. Under pressure, we enter what Milgram called an "agentic state," ceding moral responsibility to whoever gives the orders. We become instruments.</p>
  <p>Almost none of that survives scrutiny.</p>
  <p>Start with the number. The famous 65% obedience rate comes from a single variation — one of twenty-four that Milgram ran. Australian psychologist Gina Perry, who spent years in the Yale archives where Milgram's original data sits in 157 boxes, found that across all variations of the experiment, a majority of participants disobeyed. In more than half the conditions, 60% or more refused to continue. The one variation that produced the famous result was not representative of the data. It was a highlight reel.</p>
  <p>Then there is the question of what, exactly, the experimenter was doing. Milgram's published accounts described a tightly controlled procedure with four standardized "prods" — escalating verbal prompts to keep participants going. Perry's archival research, corroborated by audio recordings of the actual sessions, revealed something different. The experimenter, John Williams, routinely went off-script. He improvised. He cajoled. He applied pressure that bore little resemblance to the detached authority figure described in the published papers. What Milgram presented as obedience to a calm instruction was, in many cases, the result of active coercion.</p>
  <p>Perry also uncovered something Milgram had buried. His own assistant, Taketo Murata, conducted an unpublished analysis of participant beliefs. The finding was damning: in eighteen of twenty-three variations, participants who fully believed they were inflicting real pain administered lower shocks than those who suspected the setup was fake. Belief in the reality of the suffering predicted resistance, not compliance. Skepticism — the suspicion that none of it was real — predicted obedience. The people who went furthest were, in many cases, the people who didn't buy it.</p>
  <p>This does not make the experiments worthless. But it makes the standard interpretation — that ordinary people will blindly follow orders to harm a stranger — a story that was built on selectively presented data, unstandardized procedures, and a researcher whose career depended on a particular result.</p>
</section>

<section id="stanford-was-never-an-experiment" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Stanford Prison Study Was a Demonstration</h2>
  <p>If Milgram's experiments were more complicated than advertised, the Stanford Prison Experiment was something worse: it was staged. Not in the sense of being entirely fictional, but in the sense that the results were produced by the researchers, not observed by them.</p>
  <p>Philip Zimbardo's 1971 study — in which college students assigned to play "guards" in a basement mock prison quickly became abusive toward those assigned as "prisoners" — became the most famous illustration of situationism in all of psychology. The lesson was irresistible: put good people in a bad structure and the structure wins. It entered textbooks, TED talks, congressional testimony. Zimbardo rode it into a career as a public intellectual, complete with a bestselling book called <em>The Lucifer Effect</em>.</p>
  <p>French researcher Thibault Le Texier destroyed it. His 2018 book <em>Histoire d'un Mensonge</em> — recently published in English as <em>Investigating the Stanford Prison Experiment: History of a Lie</em> — drew on the study's own archive: video footage, transcripts, and interviews with fifteen of the original participants. What Le Texier documented was not an experiment in which situational forces spontaneously produced cruelty. It was a demonstration in which the experimenters coached the guards to be cruel, collected data selectively, and wrote conclusions that were largely determined before the study began.</p>
  <p>An eighteen-minute recording is particularly revealing. In it, Zimbardo's research assistant David Jaffe meets with a reluctant guard named John Mark and tells him, directly, that the research team needs him to be tougher. The guards were not discovering their inner sadists. They were being directed. At least one prisoner who was "released early" due to emotional breakdown had faked his distress. The experiment was terminated not because Zimbardo was shocked by what he saw, but because a visiting lawyer raised questions about the legality of holding volunteers against their will, and the remaining prisoners were increasingly resistant.</p>
  <p>In March 2025, sociologist Augustine Brannigan published a case in <em>Retraction Watch</em> arguing the study's original publication should be formally retracted. It hasn't been. Psychology textbooks continue to teach it, usually as a cautionary tale about "the power of situations" rather than as an example of scientific fraud. That framing is itself a form of moral disengagement — the discipline softening its own failure into a teachable moment.</p>
</section>

<section id="they-werent-obeying-they-were-believing" class="reveal">
  <h2>They Weren't Obeying. They Were Believing.</h2>
  <p>If blind obedience doesn't explain Milgram's results, what does? The most compelling answer comes from psychologists Alex Haslam and Stephen Reicher, whose "engaged followership" model has, over the past fifteen years, fundamentally reframed what happened in that Yale laboratory.</p>
  <p>The core insight is simple and devastating. Milgram's participants were not passively submitting to authority. They were actively identifying with it. The people who continued shocking did so because they believed in the scientific project — because they saw themselves as contributors to something important, not as instruments of someone else's will. They were not cogs in a machine. They were volunteers for a cause.</p>
  <p>The evidence is striking. When Haslam and Reicher analyzed all twenty-four of Milgram's variations, they found that obedience tracked not with the mere presence of authority but with the degree to which participants identified with the experimenter and his scientific mission. When the experiment was moved from Yale to a shabby office, obedience dropped — not because the authority was weaker, but because the scientific credibility was less convincing. When the learner was placed in the same room, obedience dropped further — because the victim became a person rather than an abstraction. And the most telling finding of all: when the experimenter used his fourth prod — the one that most resembled an actual order, "You have no other choice, you must continue" — participants almost universally refused. Direct orders killed compliance. The prod that worked best was the one that appealed to the importance of the research.</p>

  <aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"They don't shock because they are unaware of doing wrong but out of a conviction that they are doing good."</p></aside>

  <p>This is the pivot the entire field has turned on, and it deserves to land with its full weight. The old story said: <em>authority commands, conscience buckles, harm follows.</em> The new story says: <em>people choose to identify with a leader or a cause, reinterpret harmful actions as serving a greater good, and proceed not despite their moral sense but through it.</em> They are not sleepwalking into evil. They are marching, eyes open, under a banner they have chosen.</p>
  <p>A 2024 review by Birney, Reicher, and Haslam in <em>Philosophia Scientiæ</em> formalized this as a research program. Four studies — three preregistered — demonstrated that participants' willingness to follow an experimenter's harmful instructions depended on how much they identified with the scientific enterprise. Increase the prestige of the science, and compliance goes up. Make the authority figure less prototypical of the scientific community, and it goes down. Identification is the mechanism. Not obedience. Not submission. Belief.</p>
</section>

<section id="moral-disengagement-is-labor" class="reveal">
  <h2>Moral Disengagement Requires Effort</h2>
  <p>If engaged followership explains why people start down the path, Albert Bandura's framework of moral disengagement explains how they stay on it. And this is where the story gets genuinely uncomfortable, because moral disengagement is not something that happens to people. It is something they do.</p>
  <p>Bandura identified the specific cognitive moves that allow individuals to act against their own moral standards without experiencing guilt. There are eight of them, and they operate at every level of human organization, from schoolyard bullying to corporate fraud to genocide. They include: moral justification (reframing harmful acts as serving a noble purpose), euphemistic labeling (calling torture "enhanced interrogation," calling civilian deaths "collateral damage"), advantageous comparison (the harm we're doing is minor compared to what the other side does), displacement of responsibility ("I was told to do it"), diffusion of responsibility ("everyone was doing it"), distortion of consequences (minimizing or ignoring the damage), attribution of blame (the victims brought it on themselves), and dehumanization (the victims are not fully human).</p>
  <p>What makes Bandura's framework so important is not just the taxonomy. It is the verb. These are not states people fall into. They are strategies people deploy. Displacing responsibility is an action. Dehumanizing a victim is an action. Reaching for a euphemism instead of calling the thing what it is — that is an action. Each one requires psychological work: the work of looking at a harmful act and actively constructing a narrative in which it becomes acceptable.</p>
  <p>This is the hardest part of the modern picture to absorb, and it is the part most textbooks still fudge. The old situationist model was accidentally exculpatory: if the situation overwhelms everyone equally, then responsibility dissolves into circumstance. The moral disengagement model is the opposite. It says that harmful behavior requires active psychological participation. People must choose to identify with the authority. They must choose to adopt the justifying ideology. They must choose to look away from the consequences. At every step, there is a decision — not always a conscious one, not always a dramatic one, but a decision nonetheless.</p>
</section>

<section id="eichmann-was-not-thoughtless" class="reveal">
  <h2>Eichmann Was Not as Banal as Advertised</h2>
  <p>The irony is that the original case — the one that launched the entire framework — turns out to support the revision, not the original thesis. Arendt watched Eichmann in Jerusalem and saw thoughtlessness. Later historians, working from evidence Arendt did not have, saw something else entirely.</p>
  <p>In 2014, German historian Bettina Stangneth published <em>Eichmann Before Jerusalem</em>, drawing on audiotapes of interviews Eichmann gave in Argentina to the Nazi journalist Willem Sassen during the 1950s. On those tapes, the banal bureaucrat disappears. In his place is a committed Nazi ideologue who boasted about his role in the Final Solution, expressed no remorse, and described himself as a true believer in racial purity. The thoughtless functionary Arendt described was, at least in part, a performance — a legal strategy for the courtroom, not a psychological profile.</p>
  <p>Holocaust scholar Deborah Lipstadt made the same case: Eichmann's own memoir, released by Israel, is saturated with Nazi ideology. He accepted and promoted the doctrine of racial purity. If he was simply following orders, it was not because he lacked the capacity for independent thought. It was because the orders aligned with beliefs he already held.</p>
  <p>This does not disprove Arendt's insight entirely. She was right that modern bureaucracies can normalize the unthinkable — that the division of labor and the language of procedure can insulate individuals from the full moral weight of what they are doing. That observation remains powerful. But the psychological mechanism she proposed — thoughtlessness, an incapacity for reflection — was wrong about Eichmann specifically and, as the engaged followership research suggests, wrong about how ordinary people participate in harmful systems generally. The problem is not that people stop thinking. The problem is that they think their way into justifications.</p>
</section>

<section id="active-processes-can-be-interrupted" class="reveal">
  <h2>Active Processes Enable Atrocity</h2>
  <p>There is a version of this article that ends with a call to vigilance — an exhortation to "be aware of these mechanisms" so we can "prevent future atrocities." That ending would be dishonest. Awareness of moral disengagement does not reliably prevent it. Knowing about euphemistic labeling did not stop anyone from saying "enhanced interrogation" with a straight face. Knowing about displacement of responsibility did not prevent a single Abu Ghraib guard from pointing upward when asked who authorized the abuse.</p>
  <p>But there is a harder, more honest implication. If moral disengagement is an active process — something people do, not something that happens to them — then it is, at least in principle, a process that can be interrupted. Not easily. Not reliably. Not through a TED talk or a psychology seminar. But the engaged followership model suggests that identification is the key variable: people harm others when they identify more with the authority and its mission than with the victim. Anything that strengthens identification with those being harmed — proximity, shared identity, visible suffering, the simple acknowledgment that the person on the other side of the equation is a person — shifts the calculus.</p>
  <p>The Milgram data itself shows this. When the learner was in the same room, obedience dropped to 40%. When the participant had to physically place the learner's hand on the shock plate, it dropped to 30%. Closeness to the victim made moral disengagement harder to sustain. That is not a solution. But it is a mechanism — and mechanisms, unlike vague warnings about human nature, can be designed around.</p>
  <p>What the modern research removes is the alibi. For sixty years, psychology offered a story in which evil was primarily a problem of situations — of pressures so powerful that individual character barely mattered. That story was comforting in a way that its authors did not intend, because it distributed blame so widely that it effectively dissolved it. The revised story is less comfortable. It says that people who participate in harmful systems are not victims of those systems. They are participants who have done the cognitive work of making their participation feel acceptable. They have displaced responsibility. They have dehumanized the victims. They have reached for the euphemism. These are not automatic processes. They are choices — often unconscious, often incremental, often made under real pressure — but choices.</p>
  <p>The old thesis let us say: <em>anyone could have done it.</em> The new one forces a different question: <em>what did you tell yourself while you were doing it?</em></p>
</section>

